def get_covid_data(url, local_filename):
    '''
    It takes time to download the file every time
    so I downloaded the csv file and if there is a local file, we would not send another request.
    '''
    local_file_path = Path(local_filename)
    if not local_file_path.is_file():
        covid_df = pd.read_csv(url)
        covid_df.to_csv(local_file_path, index=False)
    else:
        covid_df = pd.read_csv(local_file_path)

    return covid_df

url = "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/owid/covid-19-data/master/public/data/owid-covid-data.csv"

1. Univariate Exploration¶

Here we want to understand the frequency and distribution of a single variable.

1.1 The distribution of new cases in France¶

In [82]:
# histograms of new cases(smoothed) in france 

france_new_cases_smoothed = covid_df[covid_df['location'] == 'France']['new_cases_smoothed'].dropna()

bins_sqrt = int(np.sqrt(len(france_new_cases_smoothed)))

hist_pic = sns.displot(france_new_cases_smoothed, bins=bins_sqrt, kde=True)

hist_pic.fig.set_size_inches(12, 8)

hist_pic.set(xlabel='New Cases (Smoothed)', ylabel='Frequency')

plt.show()

Observations:

  • The distribution of new COVID-19 cases (smoothed) in France is highly right-skewed.
  • The majority of the data points are concentrated in the first bin, suggesting that on most days, the number of new cases was relatively low.
  • The tail of the distribution extends to the right, suggesting that there were a few days with a higher number of new case.

def return_cols_row(list_name, cols = 4):
    n = len(list_name)
    rows = int(np.ceil(n / cols))  

    return rows, cols

# histograms of new cases(smoothed) in each country 

def create_histograms(ax, name, data = covid_df):
    continent_df = covid_df[covid_df['location'] == name]
    new_cases_smoothed = continent_df['new_cases_smoothed'].dropna()

    sns.histplot(new_cases_smoothed, bins=bins_sqrt, kde=True, ax=ax)

    ax.set_title(name)
    ax.set_xlabel('New Cases (Smoothed)')
    ax.set_ylabel('Frequency')
In [87]:
def create_plots(list_name, plot_function, data = covid_df, cols = 4):
    rows, cols = return_cols_row(list_name, cols)

    fig, axs = plt.subplots(rows, cols, figsize=(15, 5 * rows))

    axs = axs.flatten()

    for idx, name in enumerate(list_name):
        plot_function(axs[idx], name, data)

    for j in range(idx + 1, rows * cols):
        axs[j].set_visible(False)
        
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()
In [88]:
create_plots(continent_list, create_histograms, cols = 2 )

Observations:

  1. These continents all have right-skewed distributions, suggesting that there were few cases on most days.
  2. The number of new cases on the X-axis suggests that we might consider the population size when doing next steps.

def create_lineplot_cases(ax, country_name, data = covid_df):
    country_df = data[data['location'] == country_name].copy()

    ax.plot(country_df['date'], country_df['total_cases'], label='Total Cases', color='blue', linestyle='-')
    ax.plot(country_df['date'], country_df['new_cases'], label='New Cases', color='red', linestyle='--')

    ax.set_xlabel('Date')
    ax.set_ylabel('Cases')
    ax.set_title(f'{country_name}')

create_plots(target_countries_list, create_lineplot_cases, cols = 2 )

Observation:

  1. There was a sharp increase in total COVID-19 cases over a certain period, which has recently stabilized across the observed countries.
  2. Each country experienced its own peaks in new case numbers, and these surges contributed to the rapid increase in total cases. For instance, in Australia, there was a notable rise in new cases around January 2022, which coincided with a sharp uptick in the cumulative total case count.

2.2 Is there a relationship hospital beds and total deaths.¶

In [92]:
covid_df['hospital_beds_per_thousand_group'] = pd.qcut(covid_df['hospital_beds_per_thousand'], q=4, labels=False)

grouped_data = covid_df.groupby('hospital_beds_per_thousand_group').agg({
    'total_deaths_per_million': 'mean' 
}).reset_index()

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.barplot(x='hospital_beds_per_thousand_group', y='total_deaths_per_million', data=grouped_data)

plt.xlabel('Hospital Beds per Thousand Group')
plt.ylabel('Mean Total Deaths per Million')
plt.title('Total Deaths(per Million) vs Hospital Beds(per Thousand Group)')
plt.show()

Observation:

  • The data suggests an increase in the mean total deaths per million as the number of hospital beds per thousand increases.
  • This counterintuitive trend may be due to various factors, including but not limited to data quality, healthcare system efficiency, or disease severity within the population.

2.3 Is there a relationship between total cases and total deaths.¶

In [93]:
def create_scatter_plots(ax, country_name, data = covid_df):
    country_df = data[data['location'] == country_name].copy()

    ax.scatter(country_df['total_cases'], country_df['total_deaths'], color='grey')
    ax.set_title(f'{country_name}')
    ax.set_xlabel('Total Cases')
    ax.set_ylabel('Total Deaths')

create_plots(target_countries_list, create_scatter_plots, cols = 2 )

Observation:

  • The data suggests an increase in the total deaths as the number of total cases increases.
  • The rate of increase and the shape of the trend vary by country. For example, for France and Germany, there is a rapid initial increase in deaths in the initial stage; while Kenya's total deaths increase gradually.

def create_stackplot(ax, country_name, data):
    country_df = data[data['location'] == country_name].copy()

    ax.stackplot(country_df['date'], 
                 country_df['weekly_icu_admissions_per_million'], 
                 country_df['weekly_hosp_admissions_per_million'],
                 labels=['weekly_icu_admissions_per_million', 
                         'weekly_hosp_admissions_per_million'])
    ax.set_xlabel('Date')
    ax.set_ylabel('Hospital & ICU Admissions')
    ax.set_title(f'{country_name}')
    ax.legend()
In [96]:
create_plots(top_countries_list, create_stackplot, data = filtered_df, cols = 2)

Observations:

  1. All countries show fluctuations in ICU and hospital admissions over time.
  2. In contrast to other countries, which display numerous peaks, Singapore demonstrates a more gradual rise and fall in admissions, potentially reflecting a distinct approach to public policy.

3. Multi Variable Analysis¶

What would lead to covid deaths and cases¶

In [97]:
selected_features = [
    'total_cases_per_million',
    'total_deaths_per_million',
    'total_vaccinations_per_hundred', 
    'hospital_beds_per_thousand', 
    'hosp_patients_per_million',
    'icu_patients_per_million',
    'gdp_per_capita', 
    'total_tests_per_thousand',
    'human_development_index'
]

correlation_matrix_subset = covid_df[selected_features].corr()

## do not display features that has a low correlation
mask_low_corr = np.abs(correlation_matrix_subset) < 0.1

plt.figure(figsize=(20, 15)) 

cmap = sns.diverging_palette(230, 20, as_cmap=True)

sns.heatmap(correlation_matrix_subset, mask=mask_low_corr, annot=True, cmap=cmap)

plt.xticks(rotation=45, fontsize = 16)
plt.yticks(rotation=0, fontsize = 16)
plt.show()

Observation:

  1. Positive Correlation:
    • Between hospital and ICU patients per million (0.75), indicating that higher hospitalizations are associated with more intensive care cases.
    • Between total cases and deaths per million (0.56), suggesting that higher infection rates lead to more deaths.
    • Between total cases per million and total vaccinations per hundred (0.61), indicating that countries with higher infection rates may encourage more vaccinations.
    • Between total tests and total cases per million (0.57), suggesting that increased testing correlates with the detection of more cases.
  2. Negative Correlation:
    • Between ICU patients per million and hospital beds per thousand (-0.44), indicating that countries with more hospital beds might be better prepared and have fewer ICU admissions.
    • Between ICU patients per million and vaccinations per hundred (-0.27), suggesting that when vaccination rates get higher, there are less ICU patients.
  3. GDP per capita shows a weaker correlation with health metrics, implying that economic wealth might not strongly influence COVID-19 health outcomes.
